{"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0,"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[],"mount_file_id":"1bBOBLB4TntvYP6F34S-xiMTOYLdUItNh","authorship_tag":"ABX9TyN7yAvaAxSHAgFqpRUtWN5X"},"kernelspec":{"name":"python3","display_name":"Python 3"},"language_info":{"name":"python"}},"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Experiment – 8 : Support Vector Machines\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Name:** Shruti Hore  \n","\n","**PRN:** 24070126172  \n","\n","---\n","\n","**Title:** Implementation of Support Vector Machine (SVM) for Classification\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Aim:** To implement and understand the Support Vector Machine algorithm for classification tasks and evaluate its performance on a given dataset.\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Objective:**\n","\n","-\tThe classification mechanism of Support Vector Machines.\n","\n","-\tThe mathematical formulation and working principle of SVM.\n","-\tImplementing SVM for classification tasks using linear and non-linear kernels.\n","-\tEvaluating the model's performance using relevant metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score.\n","-\tVisualizing decision boundaries in SVM.\n","\n","---\n","\n","**Problem statement**\n","\n","Use the given dataset(s) to demonstrate the application of the Support Vector Machine algorithm for classification. The task is to classify the data points into different classes based on features and understand the concept of hyperplanes, margins, and kernel tricks.\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"q15JNLTglI2M"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Support Vector Machine (SVM)** is a supervised machine learning algorithm used for classification and regression tasks.  \n","In classification, SVM finds the optimal hyperplane that separates two classes with the maximum margin.\n","\n","The key idea of SVM is:\n","\n","> Find a decision boundary that maximizes the distance between the closest data points of different classes.\n","\n","These closest points are called **Support Vectors**.\n","\n","---\n","\n","## Mathematical Formulation\n","\n","### (a) Hyperplane Equation\n","\n","For binary classification:\n","\n","$$\n","w^T x + b = 0\n","$$\n","\n","Where:\n","- \\( w \\) = weight vector  \n","- \\( x \\) = feature vector  \n","- \\( b \\) = bias term  \n","\n","---\n","\n","### (b) Margin\n","\n","Distance between two supporting hyperplanes:\n","\n","$$\n","\\frac{2}{||w||}\n","$$\n","\n","SVM maximizes this margin.\n","\n","---\n","\n","### (c) Hard Margin Optimization\n","\n","$$\n","\\min_{w,b} \\frac{1}{2} ||w||^2\n","$$\n","\n","Subject to:\n","\n","$$\n","y_i (w^T x_i + b) \\ge 1\n","$$\n","\n","---\n","\n","### (d) Soft Margin Optimization\n","\n","$$\n","\\min_{w,b,\\xi} \\frac{1}{2}||w||^2 + C \\sum \\xi_i\n","$$\n","\n","Where:\n","- \\( \\xi_i \\) = slack variables  \n","- \\( C \\) = regularization parameter  \n","\n","---\n","\n","## Kernel Trick and Types of Kernel\n","\n","When data is not linearly separable, SVM uses the **Kernel Trick** to transform data into higher-dimensional space.\n","\n","Instead of explicitly transforming features, SVM uses kernel functions:\n","\n","$$\n","K(x_i, x_j)\n","$$\n","\n","### Common Kernels:\n","\n","#### 1. Linear Kernel\n","$$\n","K(x_i, x_j) = x_i^T x_j\n","$$\n","\n","#### 2. Polynomial Kernel\n","$$\n","K(x_i, x_j) = (x_i^T x_j + c)^d\n","$$\n","\n","#### 3. RBF (Radial Basis Function)\n","$$\n","K(x_i, x_j) = e^{-\\gamma ||x_i - x_j||^2}\n","$$\n","\n","---\n","\n","## Importance of SVM in Classification\n","\n","- Works well in high-dimensional space  \n","- Effective when number of features > number of samples  \n","- Robust against overfitting  \n","- Maximizes margin → better generalization  \n","- Works for both linear and non-linear problems  \n","\n","---\n","\n","## Applications of SVM\n","\n","- Face recognition  \n","- Text classification  \n","- Spam detection  \n","- Bioinformatics  \n","- Image classification  \n","\n","---\n","\n","## Performance Metrics\n","\n","### 1. Accuracy\n","\n","$$\n","Accuracy = \\frac{TP + TN}{Total}\n","$$\n","\n","Measures overall correctness.\n","\n","---\n","\n","### 2. Precision\n","\n","$$\n","Precision = \\frac{TP}{TP + FP}\n","$$\n","\n","Measures how many predicted positives are actually correct.\n","\n","---\n","\n","### 3. Recall\n","\n","$$\n","Recall = \\frac{TP}{TP + FN}\n","$$\n","\n","Measures how many actual positives are correctly predicted.\n","\n","---\n","\n","### 4. F1-Score\n","\n","$$\n","F1 = 2 \\cdot \\frac{Precision \\cdot Recall}{Precision + Recall}\n","$$\n","\n","Balance between precision and recall.\n","\n","---\n","\n","### 5. Confusion Matrix\n","\n","| Actual \\ Predicted | Positive | Negative |\n","|-------------------|----------|----------|\n","| Positive          | TP       | FN       |\n","| Negative          | FP       | TN       |\n","\n","---\n","\n","### Cross-Validation\n","\n","Cross-validation divides the dataset into multiple folds to ensure model stability and reduce overfitting.\n","\n","---\n","\n","## Algorithm (Stepwise Procedure)\n","\n","1. Load the dataset.\n","2. Perform preprocessing (handle missing values, encode features).\n","3. Split dataset into training and testing sets.\n","4. Scale features using StandardScaler.\n","5. Select SVM kernel (Linear / RBF / Polynomial).\n","6. Train model using training data.\n","7. Predict on test data.\n","8. Evaluate using performance metrics.\n","9. Visualize results (confusion matrix, decision boundary).\n","10. Compare models.\n","\n","---\n","\n","# Input & Output\n","\n","## Input:\n","- Loan Eligibility Dataset  \n","- Features: Gender, Married, Dependents, Income, LoanAmount, etc.  \n","- Target Variable: Loan_Status  \n","\n","## User Input:\n","- Kernel type  \n","- C parameter  \n","- Gamma value  \n","\n","---\n","\n","## Output:\n","\n","### Predictions:\n","- Predicted loan approval (0 = Rejected, 1 = Approved)\n","\n","### Model Evaluation Metrics:\n","- Accuracy  \n","- Precision  \n","- Recall  \n","- F1-Score  \n","- Confusion Matrix  "],"metadata":{"id":"kwZ4m5HglKfk"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# 1. Social Network Ads"],"metadata":{"id":"U6Zi7gSduuD-"}},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":17,"metadata":{"id":"H8FZXKrNjYxo","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771919097455,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":16,"user":{"displayName":"Shruti.Hore Btech2024","userId":"15026696398321729929"}}},"outputs":[],"source":["import numpy as np\n","import pandas as pd\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","from sklearn.svm import SVC\n","from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs\n","from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n","from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix"]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["data = pd.read_excel('/content/drive/MyDrive/SEMESTER 4/LABS/SML-L/datasets/(8) Social_Network_Ads.xlsx')\n","data.head()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":206},"id":"HvX2JGDBkqAJ","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1771918544460,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":1449,"user":{"displayName":"Shruti.Hore Btech2024","userId":"15026696398321729929"}},"outputId":"46f813a3-85cc-4281-d225-d6f11b4ccfff"},"execution_count":2,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["   Age  EstimatedSalary  Purchased\n","0   19            19000          0\n","1   35            20000          0\n","2   26            43000          0\n","3   27            57000          0\n","4   19            76000          0"],"text/html":["\n","  <div id=\"df-d82e61c5-a24c-4606-8c6c-39fb76eb9880\" class=\"colab-df-container\">\n","    <div>\n","<style scoped>\n","    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n","        vertical-align: middle;\n","    }\n","\n","    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n","        vertical-align: top;\n","    }\n","\n","    .dataframe thead th {\n","        text-align: right;\n","    }\n","</style>\n","<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n","  <t